Since I've exclusively done ML work on image/video signals, I had an urge to try and do some processing and 
learning on audio signals. <br>
Hence, I decided to try something fun and interesting. I wanted to take audio clips from one of my favorite podcasts, and then see if I can build a prediction model that recognizes who's voice it is in that sample. I wanted to sample audio from [very bad wizards](https://www.verybadwizards.com/) and see if I can classify audio samples that are 1s long into 3 categories (2 hosts and 1 other signal) - [david (D)](https://psychology.cornell.edu/david-pizarro), [tamler (T)](https://www.tamlersommers.com/), and others (O). <br>
So, here we, go. I'll describe each segment of the code down below.

First of all, I found a script online that helps me play audio snippets in Jupyter. The snippet is shown below. Since it is hard to "visualize" audio, we need this:


```python
import IPython.display
import numpy as np
import json


def Audio(audio: np.ndarray, sr: int):
    """
    Use instead of IPython.display.Audio as a workaround for VS Code.
    `audio` is an array with shape (channels, samples) or just (samples,)
    for mono.
    """

    if np.ndim(audio) == 1:
        channels = [audio.tolist()]
    else:
        channels = audio.tolist()

    return IPython.display.HTML("""
        <script>
            if (!window.audioContext) {
                window.audioContext = new AudioContext();
                window.playAudio = function(audioChannels, sr) {
                    const buffer = audioContext.createBuffer(
                        audioChannels.length, audioChannels[0].length, sr
                    );
                    for (let [channel, data] of audioChannels.entries()) {
                        buffer.copyToChannel(Float32Array.from(data), channel);
                    }
            
                    const source = audioContext.createBufferSource();
                    source.buffer = buffer;
                    source.connect(audioContext.destination);
                    source.start();
                }
            }
        </script>
        <button onclick="playAudio(%s, %s)">Play</button>
    """ % (json.dumps(channels), sr))

```

My first attempt was unsupervised learning. It wasn't completely garbage, but it wasn't very good. I may revisit unsupervised learning once I make some headway with supervised. But after some initial experiments, I decided to move onto supervised methods. For this, I labeled data in 3 batches with 200 1s samples each. Then I loaded them and used samples from 2 batches as training and 1 batch as test.

First attempt was at training a SVM classifier on the raw signal. You can see the code and the performance below:


```python
# loading data

import os
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split


def load_audio_file(file):
    audio_vals, freq = librosa.load(file)
    return audio_vals, freq


def load_data_batch(batch_dictionary):
    X_orig, X_fft, y = [], [], []
    for audio_file_path, lbl in batch_dictionary.items():
        assert lbl in ('D', 'T', 'O')
        audio_vals, freq = load_audio_file(audio_file_path)
        yf = np.fft.fft(audio_vals)
        X_orig.append(audio_vals)
        X_fft.append(np.abs(yf)[::5])
        y.append(lbl)
    return X_orig, X_fft, y


def load_train_test_data():
    # Train
    X_train_orig, X_train, y_train = [], [], []
    X_train_orig_batch_1, X_train_batch_1, y_train_batch_1 = (
        load_data_batch(lbl_group_1_file_lbl)
    )
    X_train_orig_batch_2, X_train_batch_2, y_train_batch_2 = (
        load_data_batch(lbl_group_2_file_lbl)
    )
    X_train_orig = X_train_orig_batch_1 + X_train_orig_batch_2
    X_train = X_train_batch_1 + X_train_batch_2
    y_train = y_train_batch_1 + y_train_batch_2

    # Test
    X_test_orig, X_test, y_test = load_data_batch(lbl_group_3_file_lbl)
    
    X_train = np.array(X_train)
    y_train = np.array(y_train)

    X_test = np.array(X_test)
    y_test = np.array(y_test)

    X_train_orig = np.array(X_train_orig)
    X_test_orig = np.array(X_test_orig)

    return X_train_orig, X_train, y_train, X_test_orig, X_test, y_test


X_train_orig, X_train, y_train, X_test_orig, X_test, y_test = (
    load_train_test_data()
)

print(X_train.shape, X_test.shape)
```

```python

random_music_file = (
    '/Users/nripesh/Projects/audio fun/1s_samples_group1/sample_38.wav'
)
audio_signal, freq = load_audio_file(random_music_file)
signal_fft = np.fft.fft(audio_signal)
xf = np.fft.fftfreq(len(audio_signal), 1 / freq)

fig, axs = plt.subplots(1, 2)
```

```python
# linear SVM - on original signal

from sklearn.svm import SVC
from collections import Counter
from sklearn.metrics import f1_score, confusion_matrix


svc_model = SVC(C=1, kernel='linear')
svc_model.fit(X_train_orig, y_train)

y_pred = svc_model.predict(X_test_orig)

print(confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred))
print('f1-score for raw signal SVM model: {:0.3f}'.format(
    f1_score(y_test, y_pred, average='micro'))
)
```

```python
# linear SVM - on FFT signal

svc_model = SVC(C=1, kernel='linear')
svc_model.fit(X_train, y_train)

y_pred = svc_model.predict(X_test)

print(confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred))
print('f1-score for fft signal SVM model: {:0.3f}'.format(
    f1_score(y_test, y_pred, average='micro'))
)
```

    [[70  5  4]
     [ 5  1  5]
     [15  8 87]]
    f1-score for fft signal SVM model: 0.790


As we can see, performance is pretty poor with SVM applied on raw signals. I actually tried few other classifiers before realizing that the problem lies elsewhere. Hence, for audio specially, it was naturally to attempt fourier transform first before trying classification. <br>
Now we'll try gradient boosted trees, which tend to be one of the best classifiers (other than neural networks).


```python
# classifier 2 -> random forest / GB tree

from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier, GradientBoostingClassifier

tree = GradientBoostingClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
tree.fit(X_train, y_train)

y_pred = tree.predict(X_test)
display(confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred))
print('f1-score for fft signal GBM model: {:0.3f}'.format(
    f1_score(y_test, y_pred, average='micro'))
)
```

Laslty, I tried a neural network with 1D convolutional network. Since the data dimension is high `4410`, I didn't want to use dense layers since they would take much longer to train.


```python
# classifier 3 -> 1D CNN

from tensorflow import keras
from tensorflow.keras import layers
from tensorflow.keras import metrics

#create model
cnn_model = keras.Sequential(
    [
        keras.Input(shape=(X_train.shape[1], 1)),
        layers.Conv1D(8, kernel_size=3, activation="relu"),
        layers.MaxPool1D(2),
        layers.Conv1D(4, kernel_size=3, activation="relu"),
        layers.MaxPool1D(2),
        layers.Flatten(),
        layers.Dense(
            3, activation="softmax", 
        ),
    ]
)

cnn_model.summary()
```

```python
from sklearn.preprocessing import OneHotEncoder

y_train_one_hot = OneHotEncoder(sparse=False).fit_transform(
    y_train.reshape(-1, 1),
).astype('float32')
y_test_one_hot = OneHotEncoder(sparse=False).fit_transform(
    y_test.reshape(-1, 1),
).astype('float32')

X_train_exp = np.expand_dims(X_train, -1)
X_test_exp = np.expand_dims(X_test, -1)

```


```python
cnn_model.compile(
    optimizer='adam', 
    loss='categorical_crossentropy',
    metrics=[
        metrics.CategoricalAccuracy(),
    ]
)

cnn_model.fit(
    X_train_exp, y_train_one_hot,
    validation_data=(X_test_exp, y_test_one_hot),
    epochs=10,
)

y_pred = cnn_model.predict(X_test_exp)
y_test_pred = np.argmax(y_pred, axis=1)

int_to_lbl_map = {0: 'D', 1: 'O', 2: 'T'}
y_test_pred = [int_to_lbl_map[y_i] for y_i in y_test_pred]

display(confusion_matrix(y_test, y_test_pred))
print('f1-score for fft signal 1D CNN model: {:0.3f}'.format(
    f1_score(y_test, y_test_pred, average='micro'))
)
```
